<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-416-295  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 416 295.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 26 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>American Mobile Satellite receives 3 bids for spacecraft.andO;(satellite communications system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Mobile Satellite Corp. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Communications SatellitesCellular radio.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AMERICAN MOBILE SATELLITE RECEIVES 3 BIDS FOR SPACECRAFT WASHINGTON, D.C.,andO;U.S.A.andP;  1990 JUN 19 (NB) -- American Mobile Satellite Corporation hasreceived three bids for its mobile satellite service, or MSS, spacecraftprocurement.andP;  One bid came from TRW, the other two from Hughes Aircraft.andM;The TRW bid includes COM DEV of Cambridge, Ontario, as a subcontractor, andboth the Hughes bids include Spar Aerospace of Toronto as a subcontractor.andO;AMSC expects to make the award by the end of July.andM;AMSC is licensed by the Federal Communications Commission to launch andoperate the MSS system for the United States in what's called the L-band.andO;AMSC will offer voice, fax, positioning, and data communications to mobilephone users throughout North America, whether on land, in the air, or at sea.andO;AMSC plans to launch its first satellite in 1993.andP;  Until then, AMSC will beoffering data services on transponders leased from an existing satellite.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900622/Press Contact: Ruth Pritchard-Kelly, AmericanMobile Satellite Corporation, 202-331-5858)</TEXT></DOC>